body:
@thesbros the change in https://github.com/electron/electron/pull/8404 is needed for > 100% DPI because otherwise the coordinates aren't scaled properly. If reverted, you'll see a white or gray borders (if not at 125%, for sure at 200% DPI)

I believe the root cause for the issue reported here is captured with https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/4045 (specifically, a similar issue was reported with https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/8546 which got merged w/ 4045).

Can anyone try the demo program on Windows 7? My guess is that the size is calculated correctly there

![border2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/25285792/23391604/16674284-fd2b-11e6-8012-c31616785579.jpg)
![border](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/25285792/23391605/1a311ffc-fd2b-11e6-9a0c-9a9f79da144e.jpg)

@bsclifton Here is the screen shot of the white border. I no longer have the code because it did not fix my issue and I overrode it with other tests. @thesbros tested this example as well so he might be able to provide the code of what we did. Also I am not very familiar with the `native_window_views.cc` code and I may have missed a step. Can you please provide more details of how you override the bounds (x,y) and also does it work for you, have you tested it?

@radencode here's an example you can try to get more info (I don't have electron compiled and ready to test at the moment unfortunately and it's already 2am)

```diff
diff --git a/atom/browser/native_window_views_win.cc b/atom/browser/native_window_views_win.cc
index 1b523e9..100f370 100644
--- a/atom/browser/native_window_views_win.cc
+++ b/atom/browser/native_window_views_win.cc
@@ -5,6 +5,7 @@
 #include "atom/browser/browser.h"
 #include "atom/browser/native_window_views.h"
 #include "content/public/browser/browser_accessibility_state.h"
+#include <cmath>

 namespace atom {

@@ -147,6 +148,51 @@ bool NativeWindowViews::PreHandleMSG(
       }
       return false;
     }
+
+    //\see WM_GETMINMAXINFO - https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms632626(v=vs.85).aspx
+    case WM_GETMINMAXINFO: {
+      MINMAXINFO* mmi = (MINMAXINFO*)l_param;
+
+      if (IsMaximized()) {
+        HWND hwnd = GetAcceleratedWidget();
+        RECT window_rect;
+        if (!GetWindowRect(hwnd, &window_rect)) {
+          return false;
+        }
+
+        HMONITOR monitor = MonitorFromRect(&window_rect, MONITOR_DEFAULTTONULL);
+        if (!monitor) {
+          return false;
+        }
+
+        MONITORINFO monitor_info = { 0 };
+        monitor_info.cbSize = sizeof(monitor_info);
+        GetMonitorInfo(monitor, &monitor_info);
+
+        RECT work_area = monitor_info.rcWork;
+        RECT monitor_rect = monitor_info.rcMonitor;
+
+        mmi->ptMaxPosition.x = std::abs(work_area.left - monitor_rect.left);
+        mmi->ptMaxPosition.y = std::abs(work_area.top - monitor_rect.top);
+        mmi->ptMaxSize.x = std::abs(work_area.right - work_area.left);
+        mmi->ptMaxSize.y = std::abs(work_area.bottom - work_area.top);
+        mmi->ptMinTrackSize.x = 2;
+        mmi->ptMinTrackSize.y = 2;
+
+        *result = 0;
+        return true;
+      }
+
+    //\see WM_WINDOWPOSCHANGING - https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms632653(v=vs.85).aspx
+    case WM_WINDOWPOSCHANGING: {
+      WINDOWPOS* wp = (WINDOWPOS*)l_param;
+      if (IsMaximized()) {
+        LOG(ERROR) << "WM_WINDOWPOSCHANGING; position=[" << wp->x << "," << wp->y <<
+        "]; width=[" << wp->cx << "," << wp->cy;
+        return false;
+      }
+    }
+
     default:
       return false;
   }
```

In `WM_GETMINMAXINFO`, I used the same calculations which Chromium uses so this should be accurate (see [`ui/views/win/hwnd_message_handler.cc`](https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src.git/+/56.0.2924.87/ui/views/win/hwnd_message_handler.cc#178) in Chromium 54 or newer)

In `WM_WINDOWPOSCHANGING`, I just show how you can log the params. This should help with understanding what the x/y and width/height are set to. Because of the borders, I believe these values are incorrect.  If you wanted to adjust these, you can set the `x`/`y` and `cx`/`cy` for the `wp` variable, set *result = 0, and return true.
